item.title: Hovea montana
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: White variant in front of the typical coloured species.

item.title: Dianella tasmanica
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Growing on a flank of Mount Stirling at about 1300m altitude. Dianella tasmanica is a common species in the area but this one seems to have a thicker flower stem and more closely clustered flowers. Three photos.

item.title: Parsonsia brownii
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Creeper growing through low shrubbery. One of a young group of plants to maximum height of about 1m. Looks to have potential to climb much higher, similar to clematis. Tiny flower. Diameter 5mm. 2 pics uploaded (one of leaves).

item.title: Prostanthera galbraithiae
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Vulnerable. Approx. 850 plants remain in natural habitat (2006 census). This one in a patch of about thirty in natural bush between commercial pine plantations. Two pics uploaded.

item.title: Acrothamnus hookeri
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Not the best photo or example but at least it's a record. Stunted plant about 50cm high at elevation circa 1300m not long after snow melt. Have also seen plants at lower elevations (around 800m) to about 3m high with thick clusters of flowers.

item.title: Olearia tenuifolia
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Location approximate.

item.title: Leionema bilobum subsp. serrulatum
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Fairly common between Gembrook and Noojee. Have seen them in damp valleys right on the edge of watercourses as well as on an elevated rocky escarpment at 600m.

item.title: Menura novaehollandiae
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Getting to know each other. Three short videos uploaded taken during ten minutes of observation.

item.title: Acacia kettlewelliae
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Much smaller (or younger) plant at 3 metres high, and appears to be slightly later flowering than previous observation. Growing at 1100m altitude amongst A.obliquinervia

item.title: Acacia kettlewelliae
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Location approximate. Numerous trees up to 6 or 8m in height along 2km stretch of road. Growing at about 500m - 600m altitude.

item.title: Veronica serpyllifolia
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Tiny grassland plant. 10cm high. Flower 5mm diameter. 100s of plants over a few square metres.

item.title: Veronica serpyllifolia
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Tiny plant in damp grassland. 10cm high. Flowers 5mm diameter. 100s of plants over about 5 square metres.

item.title: Grevillea chrysophaea (Gippsland form)
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Possibly the Holey Plains Form as it was observed adjacent to the Holey Plains State Park. VicFlora has this form with narrower leaves (to 5mm) and less hairy flowers than other forms of G.chrysophaea. I did not measure the leaves but they appeared to be a little larger than as stated; perhaps to 1cm.

item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Adding an extra two leaf images. Different plant and location to previous observation.

item.dc:creator: abcmaps

item.title: Hovea asperifolia subsp. asperifolia
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Gembrook variant. Small upright tree or shrub. Tallest in this community is over 2 metres in height.

item.title: Viburnum tinus
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Introduced species. Recently noticed growing on roadside reserve. Identified by Lewis Hiller - Plant Identification Australia (Facebook).

item.title: Daviesia buxifolia
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: New record. Flowering September. Verification of I.D. would be appreciated. 2m tall shrubs. Growing on dry rocky slope near river.

item.title: Utricularia gibba
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Growing in shallow water in a forest dam. Noticed in two places about 1km apart. Identified as such by Kelly Bollinger (Facebook - Plant Identification Australia). Three photos uploaded. Native species. Common elsewhere in Australia but unusual in Victoria.

item.title: Gaultheria appressa
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: In flower. November / December.

item.title: Gaultheria appressa
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: With fruit. Dargo High Plains Road at altitude about 1200m.

item.title: Trachymene humilis subsp. humilis
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: I think this might be a Trachymene humilis subsp. humilis (Alpine Trachymene) but am not sure. Growing at about 1400m altitude between Omeo and Dargo. Stalks about 10cm. Plants appear to be growing individually rather than as a matted group as seen at higher altitudes. Three images uploaded.

item.title: Viola arvensis
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Noticed below the summit of Mount Buller and again near the summit of Corn Hill. In grassy areas.

item.title: Erythranthe moschata
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Scattered in moist gullies with running water near Mount Buller and along Mount Buller Tourist Road.

item.title: Verbena spp.
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Verbena officinalis has been suggested to me. One plant growing beside Stirling Road at Mount Buller in a rocky, dry environment. Altitude 1500 - 1600m. Twiggy shrub about 1 metre high. See other photos. Unfortunately pics not quite sharp enough to see leaf in detail. The flower and what you can see of the leaves certainly looks like Verbena.

item.title: Olearia aff. ramulosa (Omeo)
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Observed at Snowy Plains near Licola. Altitude 1600mm growing in a dry, exposed area.

item.title: Veronica subtilis
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Growing on Snow Plains about 1600m altitude in the Victorian Alpine Area near Licola. Further advice or confirmation re ID welcome.

item.title: Ranunculus pimpinellifolius
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Need an I.D. please. On Dargo High Plains altitude 1500m about 5km from the Sedum Acre posted yesterday. Looks similar but could be a Ranunculus species. Very hairy stems and what seem to be the leaves. Flowering early December. This one was growing in a wet area. Suggestions have been Ranunculus collinus, Ranunculus amplus or another Sedum species. Can anyone help please? Thank you.

item.title: Sedum acre
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Growing amongst rocks at altitude 1500m. Dargo High Plains.

item.title: Oxylobium arborescens
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Small community of about 6 plants observed. Identified from Costermans 'Native Trees & Shrubs of South-Eastern Australia' and RBG 'Vicflora' website.

item.title: Olearia lirata
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Olearia lirata possibly with a fungal infection

item.title: Tetratheca stenocarpa
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Widespread in the Hoddles Creek - Gembrook area. Scattered and sparse blooms through late autumn and early winter but putting on a colourful show in August, September and October.

item.title: Correa reflexa var. lobata
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Shrub View. May 2016. Flowers can be seen from late April to August.

item.title: Correa reflexa var. lobata
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: One for the Archives. Photographed April 2016. Apparently rare in Victoria but prolific between Gembrook, Hoddles Creek and Powelltown.

item.title: Hibbertia empetrifolia subsp. empetrifolia s.s.
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: My uneducated guess is H.empetrifolia but I have some doubt as I cannot see any pics of that species on natureshare. Showy plant at the moment which trails, scrambles and climbs over other plants and logs. Locally common in Gembrook area. Please comment if I.D. is incorrect and I will change it. Underside of foliage has fine sparse hairs along the vein which appears to concur with Vicflora description.

item.title: Goodia lotifolia s.s.
item.dc:creator: abcmaps
item.description: Beside Mount Riddell Walking Track. Flora of Melbourne mentions alternative name 'Clover Tree'. Not sure if s.l. or s.s.
